<exercise checkit-seed="0003" checkit-slug="FO3" checkit-title="Substitution for First-Order IVPs">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Use an appropriate substitution
      to show that all of the following ODEs may be transformed into
      the same linear ODE.
      (Do not fully solve these ODEs.)
    </p>
    <ol>
        <li><m>3 \, t^{7} y^{8} + 7 \, {y'} = 5 \, t^{4} y</m></li>
        <li><m>40 \, t^{5} + 30 \, t^{4} y + 8 = 3 \, t^{7} - 6 \, {y'}</m></li>
        <li><m>3 \, t^{9} - t {y'} + y = 5 \, t^{5} y</m></li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <ol>
            <li><p>Let <m>u = \frac{1}{y^{7}}</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Let <m>u = 8 \, t + 6 \, y</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Let <m>u = \frac{y}{t}</m>.</p></li>
    </ol>
      <p>
          All ODEs transform into
          <m>5 \, t^{4} u + {u'} = 3 \, t^{7}</m>.
      </p>
  </answer>
</exercise>
